Data manipulation language: insert, update, and delete.

Data manipulation language changes the rows inside tables. Insert adds a row; listing the columns explicitly is strongly preferred over a positional insert, which silently breaks the day a new column is added. Update modifies existing rows that match a where clause. And delete removes rows that match a where clause.

The single most expensive mistake in sequel is an update or a delete without a where clause. Both operate on every row in the table by default. Always preview with a select using the same predicate before running the write, and wrap the write in a transaction when you can.

The example inserts a new customer, Eve, with an explicit column list rather than relying on positional order. It then updates Eve's email, with a where clause pinning the change to her id, and finally deletes Eve, again with a where clause. Every update and delete carries a where, so none of them touch the whole table.
